Indonesia.impact:
The Financial Service Authority Circular Letter No.14/SEOJK.07/2014 on Confidentiality and Security of Consumers' Private Information and/or Data 2014 (SEOJK No.14/SEOJK.07/2014) has been revoked according to Article 61 letter a POJK 6/POJK.07/2022 concerning Consumer and Community Protection in the Financial Services Sector. 

The protection of consumers’ data and information in the financial services sector is governed in OJK Regulation Number 22 of 2023 on Consumer and Public Protection in the Financial Services Sector (POJK 22/2023). In line with Law Number 27 of 2022 on Personal Data Protection, POJK 22/2023 governs the obligation for Financial Services Providers (FSPs) to acquire the data subject’s consent (Article  20) and to provide adequate or equivalent level of data protection (Article 21). 

The banking sector has additional references regarding bank secrecy as stipulated in the Financial Services Authority (OJK) Regulation No. 44/2024 on Bank Secrecy. Article 2 requires banks and affiliated parties to maintain the confidentiality of the information of depositors and their deposits and/or Investors and their Investments (specifically for sharia commercial bank customers). However, Article 3 of the Regulation allows such information to be disclosed for the purpose of:
●	judicial interests in civil cases between the Bank and the Customer, the Customer and the Customer, and related to the Customer;
●	judicial interests in criminal cases;
●	requests from a curator appointed based on a commercial court decision regarding bankruptcy or requests from a liquidator appointed based on a court ruling in the context of settling assets;
●	requests, approvals, or powers of attorney from Depositors and/or Investor Customers made in writing;
●	requests from the legal heirs of Depositors and/or Investor Customers who have died;
●	exchange of information between Banks;
●	fulfilling mutual assistance in criminal matters;
●	requests for financial information for tax purposes based on provisions of laws and regulations;
●	interests of other agencies for the purpose of organizing the state at the central level and the public interest in accordance with the duties and authorities in the Law;
●	interests in carrying out tasks in the fields of monetary, macroprudential, and payment systems by Bank Indonesia;
●	interests of implementing tasks in the field of Deposit Insurance and resolution by the Deposit Insurance Agency;
●	implementation of cooperation agreements between state authorities that have been signed reciprocally; and
●	settlement of receivables that have been submitted to the State Receivables Affairs Committee.

