Mongolia.impact:
The law prescribes conditions and requirements for web site service provider, including the monitoring requirements. 

According to Part 7, under Article 7.3, platforms that allow users to create or comment on content are required to actively monitor user activity and ensure compliance with content standards set by law. 
7.3.1. to mandatorily use the word-filter software operated by the Regulatory Committee;
7.3.2. to provide the customers who agreed the conditions and requirements that reminds the use of service in accordance with Mongolian relevant legislations with possibility to create content;
7.3.3. in case customer considers the content created by other customers illegal or having negative impact on public ethics, to create possibility for the customer to express opinion or to erase such content depending from the number of the opinions;
7.3.4. to place the customer’s IP address publicly visible on top of the content created by the customer;
7.3.5. to erase the content if deems the content created by the customer violates provisions of the chapter 4.In particular, Article 4 prohibits the creation or distribution of content that includes pornography or erotic material, advertisements or expressions promoting criminal acts, content that threatens national solidarity or advertises terrorism, content that incites public disorder, promotes violent religious doctrines, or relates to the unauthorized promotion of drugs and substances. 

Person whose interest has been violated or the web site service provider may submit the IP address of the customer who created a content which violated chapter 4 of the present General Conditions and Requirements to the Regulatory Committee (Article 7.4). 

Additionally, under Article 6.3, content aggregator also required to monitor whether the content to be delivered to customer violate the article 4 of the present General Conditions and Requirements.  In the event the article 4 of the present General Conditions and Requirements is violated, technical possibility and condition to immediately intercept the violation shall be created (Article 6.4).

Russian Federation.impact:
Article 14 Providing the national regime for procurement 

14.1 When carrying out procurements, a national treatment regime is provided, ensuring that goods originating from a foreign state or a group of foreign states, as well as works and services respectively performed or provided by a foreign citizen or foreign legal entity, are granted equal conditions with goods of Russian origin, works, and services respectively performed or provided by a Russian citizen or Russian legal entity, except in cases where the Government of the Russian Federation adopts measures provided for in paragraph 1 of part 2 of this article.

14.2 The Government of the Russian Federation has the right, taking into account the provisions of part 3 of this article, to adopt measures establishing:

a) A ban on the procurement of goods (including those supplied as part of purchased works or services) originating from foreign states, as well as works and services respectively performed or provided by foreign entities;

b) Restrictions on the procurement of goods (including those supplied as part of purchased works or services) originating from foreign states, as well as works and services respectively performed or provided by foreign entities;

c) Preferential treatment for goods of Russian origin (including those supplied as part of purchased works or services), as well as works and services respectively performed or provided by Russian entities.

14.4 If the Government of the Russian Federation establishes a ban on procurement as specified in subparagraph "a" of paragraph 1 of part 2 of this article:

a) Any bid for procurement that includes an offer to supply such a good originating from a foreign state shall be rejected in accordance with this Federal Law;

b) A contract for the supply of such a good originating from a foreign state cannot be concluded with a sole supplier;

c) During contract execution, the replacement of the good with one originating from a foreign state for which such a ban has been established is not permitted.

In Russian Federation, a unitary enterprise is recognized as a commercial organization that does not possess the right of ownership over the property assigned to it by the owner. Only state and municipal enterprises may be established in the form of unitary enterprises. The property of a unitary enterprise is owned by the Russian Federation, a constituent entity of the Russian Federation, or a municipal entity.

Paragraph 4 of Article 8 of the Federal Law No. 161-FZ of November 14, 2002 "On State and Municipal Unitary Enterprises"states that a unitary enterprise may be established in the following cases:

1. as provided by federal laws, acts of the President of the Russian Federation, or acts of the Government of the Russian Federation;
2. to support the activities of federal executive authorities responsible for the development and implementation of state policy and legal regulation in the fields of defense, intelligence, mobilization preparedness and mobilization in the Russian Federation, transport security, international relations, state protection, internal affairs, civil defense, protection of the population and territories from natural and man-made emergencies, fire safety, water safety, the activities of the Russian National Guard Troops, the federal executive authority responsible for ensuring national security, and the federal executive authority responsible for the logistical and financial support of the highest state authorities of the Russian Federation;
3. to carry out activities in areas of natural monopolies;
4. to support the livelihoods of the population in the regions of the Far North and other equivalent territories;
5. to carry out activities in the fields of culture, the arts, cinematography, and the preservation of cultural assets;
6. to carry out activities outside the territory of the Russian Federation;
7. to engage in activities related to the handling of radioactive waste, including its disposal; the use of port infrastructure facilities that are exclusively federally owned; and the assignment of federal nuclear organization status to unitary enterprises.

Furthermore, the Preseidential Decree No.1009  approved an annexed list identifying enterprises and joint-stock companies considered strategic, due to their importance to national security, defense, energy, telecommunications, and other key sectors. According to Article 2 of the Decree, if the Government of the Russian Federation decides that an enterprise is no longer to be classified as strategic, or that the state may reduce its ownership stake, such enterprises may be included in the federal privatization plan. Specifically, federal state unitary enterprises listed in Section 1 of the annex may be transformed into joint-stock companies, with 100% of shares initially owned by the federal government.

Notably, some of the enterprises listed in Section 1 are related to digital trade, including the All-Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company, the Information Telegraph Agency of Russia (ITAR-TASS), Mosfilm Film Concern, the International News Agency "Russia Today," and the Russian Television and Radio Broadcasting Network.

According to Article 6 of the Federal Law No.57, business activities of strategic importance for the national defence and state security which must obtain preliminary approval as provided in the Law include, among others, (i) development and production of encryption (cryptographic) aids, or informational and telecommunication systems protected with encryption (cryptographic) aids that are subject to licensing under the national legislation; (ii) distribution of encryption (cryptographic) aids; (iii) engineering maintenance of encryption (cryptographic) aids; (iv) information encryption services; (v) activities to identify electronic devices intended for the covert acquisition of information in premises and technical facilities; (vi) implementation of television broadcasting in the territory within which resides a population that constitutes half or more than half of the population of a constituent entity of the Russian Federation; (vii) implementation of activities by an economic entity occupying a dominant position; (viii)  implementation of activities by an economic entity that is the operator of an electronic platform, the operator of a specialized electronic platform in accordance with the legislation of the Russian Federation.

Article 7 of the Law enlists the investment transactions for which a preliminary approval must be obtained. Transactions subject to preliminary approval are the following:
1) transactions resulting in the acquisition by a foreign investor: 
a) the right to dispose directly/indirectly of more than 50% (25% or more in case of a company that is of strategic importance and which uses a subsoil area of federal importance) of the total number of votes of the voting stocks (shares) constituting the authorised capital of company of strategic importance;
b) the right to appoint a one-man executive body and/or more than 50% (25% or more in case of a company that is of strategic importance and which uses a subsoil area of federal importance) of the composition of a collective executive body of company.
2) transactions aimed at the acquisition by a foreign investor of the right to dispose directly/indirectly of the stocks (shares) constituting the authorised capital of a business association which has strategic importance and uses a subsoil tract of federal importance, if that foreign investor has the right to directly or indirectly dispose of at least 25 % and up to 75 % of the total number of the votes accounting for the voting stocks (shares) which constitute the authorised capital of such business association; 
3) contracts for a foreign investor excercising the functions of the manager (managing organisation) in respect of a company of strategic importance;
4) transactions aimed at acquisition by a foreign state, international organisation, foreign investor that does not supply information or by an organisation controlled by them of the right to dispose directly/indirectly of over 25% of the total number of votes of the voting stocks (shares) constituting the authorised capital of an economic company of strategic importance;
5) other transactions and agreements aimed at the transfer to a foreign investor of the right to determine the decisions of managerial bodies of a company of strategic importance, including the conditions under which it exercises business activities;
6) transactions envisaging the acquisition for ownership, possession or use of property which is classified as property, plant and equipment of a business association of strategic importance and whose value makes up 25 and more per cent of the balance-sheet value of assets of such business association calculated as of the last accounting date according to the data of its accounting (financial) statements;
7) other actions as a result of which a foreign investor acquires the right of defining the decisions of the managerial bodies of the business association of strategic importance, for instance the conditions of its pursuance of entrepreneurial activities.

To date, there are no reports of telecommunication or ICT investments having been blocked by the Russian Government on national interest grounds. 

With regard to acquisitions, some investment transactions may require prior approval by the Federal Antimonopoly Service. Notification and approval requirements established by the Federal Law No. 57-FZ are separate from the merger control regime provided for by Russian antitrust law. However, where transactions require clearance under both regimes, the Federal Antimonopoly Service (FAS) will postpone the merger control review until clearance under the Strategic Investment Law is obtained. If a transaction is blocked under the Federal Law No. 57-FZ process, this automatically constitutes the basis for the FAS to deny merger clearance.

Article 5 of the Law states that cases on the suspension of the exercise of corporate rights by a foreign holding company in relation to an economically significant organization (hereinafter also referred to as suspension of the exercise of rights) shall be considered by the Arbitration Court of the Moscow Region in accordance with the rules provided for by the Arbitration Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, with the features established by this article. 

Furthermore, the following persons have the right to apply to the arbitration court with an application for suspension of the exercise of rights:

1) the federal executive body authorized to do so by the Government of the Russian Federation;

2) shareholders (participants) of an economically significant organization, regardless of the number of shares they own (the size of their shares in the authorized capital);

3) the sole executive body or a member of the board of directors (supervisory board) of an economically significant organization; 

4) persons specified in paragraph 1 of part 1 of article 7 of this Federal Law, provided that their share of direct and (or) indirect participation in a foreign holding company is no less than 50 percent, or no less than 30 percent

Article 6 further outlines what happens when a Russian arbitration court suspends the corporate rights of a foreign holding company (FHC) in relation to an economically significant organization (ESO). The main consequences include the loss of voting rights, restrictions on share transactions, and forced transfer of shares to the ESO itself.

Clear copyright exceptions are found in Articles 1273-1280 of the Part IV of the Civil Code according to which the exclusive rights of an author on his/her works are limited by a number of allowed free uses. 

The Article 1273 allows reproduction of a lawfully disclosed work when necessary and for purely personal purposes, without paying royalties and getting the consent of the author of the work except for architectural works, databases and computer programs, among others. The rest of provisions in the above/mentioned articles (Articles 1274-1280) allow, subject to the terms and conditions laid down therein: 
- use of copyrighted works for informational, scientific, educational and cultural purposes; 
- use of copyrighted photographic works, works of architecture and works of art which are permanently located at a place freely available to the public;
- use of musical works in the official or religious ceremonies; 
- use of copyrighted works for the purposes of law enforcement; 
- recording of copyrighted works by broadcasting organisations for the short-term usage; 
- making changes to software and databases for the purposes of functioning; archiving the copy of software and database and de-compilation of software.

Article 10.1.3: The organizer of information dissemination on the Internet is obliged to store on the territory of the Russian Federation:

1) information on the facts of receipt, transmission, delivery and (or) processing of voice information, written text, images, sounds, video or other electronic messages of Internet users and information about these users within one year from the date of the end of such actions;

2) text messages of Internet users, voice information, images, sounds, video, other electronic messages of Internet users up to six months from the end of their reception, transmission, delivery and (or) processing. The procedure, terms and scope of storage of the information specified in this subparagraph shall be established by the Government of the Russian Federation.

