Thailand.impact:
The Patent Act 1979 provides that an applicant for a patent shall possess one of the following qualifications (Section 14, Part 1 concerning Applications for patents):
(1) a Thai national or a juristic person having its headquarters located in Thailand;
(2) a national to a convention/international agreement on patent protection, which Thailand is also a party;
(3) a national of a country which allows Thai nationals/juristic persons having headquarters to apply for patents in that country;
(4) domiciled or an industrial or commercial establishment in Thailand or a country party to a convention or an international agreement on patent protection to which Thailand is also a party.

(*Remark: Section 14 of the Patent Act 1979 is amended by Section 5 of the Patent Act 1999 (No.3).)

To balance the interests between the copyright owner and the public interests, the the 'Three-Step Test' of the TRIPs Agreement (Berne Convention) and the 'Fair Use' doctrines can be found in  Section 32 of the Copyrights Act 1994, the copyright infringement exemptions. Section 32 (paragraph 1) states that any infringement of a copyrighted work of another person, which does not conflict with normal exploitation and does not unreasonably prejudice the legitimate interests of the author, shall not be deemed and an infringement of copyright.

Section 32 (paragraph 2) states that subject to the provision of paragraph one, any act against the copyrighted work in paragraph one shall not be deemed an infringement of copyright provided that the act is each of the followings:
(1) research or study of the work provided that such not for profit;
(2) use for personal benefit or the family  benefit including close relatives;
(3) review, accompanied by an acknowledgment of the copyright owner;
(4) news reporting through mass communication;
(5) use (reproduction, adaptation, etc.) of judicial or authorized officials' proceedings;
(6) use (reproduction, adaptation, etc.) by a teacher for teaching such act is non-profit;
(7) use (reproduction, adaptation, etc.) by a teacher or an educational institution for distributing or selling such act is non-profit;
(8) use as part of questions and answers in an examination.

Note that the Copyright Act was last amended by the Copyright Act (No.5) B.E.2565.

