Thailand.impact:
Section 7 Chapter 1: Rights and Duties in Respect of Health of the National Health Act states that Personal health information shall be kept confidential unless receiving consent from the data subject or requiring by a specific law. Importantly, no person shall disclose certain information to cause damage to the data. Provided in Section 49, any person who violates the law by unlawfully disclosure of other health information shall be liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months, or to a fine not exceeding ten thousand Thai Baht, or to both. 

Similarly, the Regulation of the Ministry of Public Health on the Protection and Management of Personal Health Information issued under the National Health Act Clause 13 states that personal health information, including height, weight, blood type, medical history, and other relevant details, deems confidential. The health information shall be kept confidential unless receiving consent or appointing a representative by the subject data. Clause 19 stipulates the conditions of the personal health information disclosure:
(1) the disclosure must be done within the intended purpose;
(2) the dissemination of the disclosed personal health information is prohibited;
(3) the disclosure must not cause any damage to the data subject.

