Thailand.impact:
Regarding the Commission of Computer-Related Offences Act (known as the Computer Crimes Act (CCA)), the services provider must remove computer data once it has received a notification from the Minister of Digital Economy and Society (MDES) to discontinue the dissemination of certain data (Section 15). However, if the service provider intentionally supports or gives consent at the offenses in a computer crime, it shall be liable to the same penalty: fines, imprisonment, or both as the offender. To clarify, the computer offenses include (Section 14): 
(1) dishonest or by deceitful use computer data/ system causing loss to the public:
(2) computer data/system causing loss to national security, economic security, and public interest; 
(3) computer data/system constituting an offense relating to the security of the Kingdom or terrorism;
(4) computer data/system of a pornographic nature;
(5) disseminating/forwarding with the knowledge about the data under (1), (2), (3), and (4). 

In August 2023, the MDES announced its intention to initiate legal proceedings against Facebook. The MDES stated that Facebook did not, as asked by the Ministry, remove advertisements for "scams" such as crypto trading or other investments. According to section 15 of the Computer Crime Act, any service provider who cooperates, consents, or conspires to commit an offence in a computer system under their control shall be liable to the same penalty as the offender.

